ce:section.ce:para:
Unfortunately, very little literature is available concerning the exact composition (various elements and their relative concentrations) of the final battery leachates and these few studies provide very scattered results, as the composition is dependent on the initial composition of the battery and leaching method. Following these observations, we decided to establish a typical leachate composition by calculating the mean concentration of each ion in the leachate concentrations from the literature, as well as the concentration range and the pH range. This data (Table 2

                        ) should help provide a standardized approach to working with LIB leachates. We were sometimes able to calculate the leachate composition from the initial composition of the cathode materials, pulp density and leaching efficiency (values are in bold Table 2
                        ) according to the following formula: CL = PD x PB x E, where CL is the concentration of lithium in the leachate (in g/L), PD is the pulp density (in g/L), PB is the weight percentage of lithium in the cathode material and E the leaching efficiency of lithium.

Macrocyclic compounds have been often reported for the selective recovery of lithium. They are usually composed of multiple ketones or urea functions that are strategically placed to form microcavities in the same way as CEs. For instance, 3-fold [124], 4-fold [125] and 5-fold [126] symmetric cyclic macro compounds were reported in the literature (Table 5
                           ). The association constants of lithium with such compounds are all rather high. However, the gap between the association constant with lithium and with other ions decreases with the increasing size of the macrocycles, i.e., the selectivity towards lithium decreases with bigger macrocycles. Additionally, acyclic analogues were also synthesized and it was shown that they were not as efficient as the cyclic version, which is in alignment with the “macrocyclic effect”, cyclic ligands providing better complexation stability and selectivity over their open chain analogues [125]. Metallomacrocyclic compounds containing ruthenium metals are also reported (Table 5
                           ) and showed interesting association constants with lithium while maintaining good selectivity [127,128]. The lithium-selective macrocycle synthesized by Grote et al. showed a Li/Na selectivity of 10,000:1. The authors explain that this points to the fact that the combination of two electron-donating alkyl side chains on ruthenium is beneficial for ion binding [128]. Finally, the structure of some macrocycles also allows for 1:2 complexation, i.e., one complexing agent for the simultaneous complexation of two lithium ions. Gohil et al. and Chen et al. propose compounds, which can structurally arrange themselves to host exclusively lithium and more particularly to host more than one lithium ion per compound (an average of 1.35 Li+ ions in Gohil's study) [129,130]. A study of the binding models shows that the insertion of a second Li+ ion is in fact thermodynamically favorable allowing such a high sorption capacity, however the presence of competitive ions reduces the maximum Li+ uptake to only 69 % [129].

Another class of excellent lithium selective extractants are phosphor-based systems such as tributyl phosphate (TBP), trioctylphosphine oxide (TOPO) and tributylphosphine oxide (TBPO), which are often used in combination with ionic liquids (Table 5
                           ). Overall, compounds containing a high number of electro-attractive oxygen and phosphor atoms seem to permit great complexation with lithium, since the reported lithium uptakes are all above 80 %. The various studies show that the heteroatoms of the various extractants assemble in a certain way to allow as many interactions as possible with the lithium ions. For example, in the system designed by Zhang et al., single crystal X-ray analyses confirmed that binuclear Li+ complexes were formed with co-coordination of acetonitrile solvent, TBPO or TBP to yield a 2:2:2 stoichiometry (Li+:[L]−:solvent/co-ligand) (Table 5
                           ) [141]. Meanwhile, TOPO formed trinuclear complexes in which three metal centers are bridged by the O-donor atom of TOPO, to yield a tetrahedral [Li3O]-core. Unfortunately, some of the systems do not allow for selectivity towards lithium. Recepoğlu et al. designed functionalized hazelnut shell waste with phosphorylated groups, for the recovery of lithium with a bio sorbent [138] but their assembly was not selective towards lithium. The authors explain that this may be due to the competition of notably Ca and Mg which possess higher valence and atomic radius, i.e., stronger interactions with the phosphorus-based extractants, compared to monovalent ions.
